    "The combination of inequalities (55) and (56) finally yields the estimated dt D 2 (h|h eq)(t) + d dt ( η τ e -τ t) ≤ -I D (h|h eq)(t),(57)where we have conveniently denotedη = η (1 + ∥log(1 + w)∥ L q ′ (I) ∥h eq ∥ L ∞ (R+,L q (I)) + ∥log 2 (1 + w)∥ 1/2 L q ′ (I) ∥h eq ∥ 1/2 L ∞ (R+,L q (I))).Now, integrating (53) over t ∈ R + and using that H(h|h eq)(t) is nonnegative for any t ∈ R +, we infer the L 1 (R +) integrability of I H (h|h eq)(t) since∫ R+ I H (h|h eq)(s)ds ≤ ζ(1 + H(h|h eq)(0))(58)for some ζ > 0, from which also follows D 2 (h|h eq) ∈ L 1 (R +) thanks to relation (54).",
    "Moreover, inequality (57) tells us that the quantity D 2 (h|h eq)(t) + η τ e -τ t is decreasing in time and, since it belongs to L 1 (R +), the latter must decay at infinity at least like O (t -1).",
    "These considerations finally lead to the decay estimate ∥h -h eq ∥ L 1 (I) ≤ 2D(h|h eq)(t) = O (t -1/2), t → +∞, where the inequality linking the L 1 norm with the Hellinger distance is obtained using the simple relation|a-b| = | √ a - √ b| ( √ a + √ b)and two successive applications of Cauchy-Schwarz inequality.",
